  "prompt": "How do I find the average acceleration?",
  "response": "To find the average acceleration, you can use the formula:\n\n\\[ \\text{Average Acceleration} (a_{\\text{avg}}) = \\frac{\\Delta v}{\\Delta t} \\]\n\nwhere:\n- \\( \\Delta v \\) is the change in velocity (final velocity minus initial velocity)\n- \\( \\Delta t \\) is the change in time (final time minus initial time)\n\nThe steps to find the average acceleration are as follows:\n\n1. Determine the initial velocity (\\( v_i \\)) and the final velocity (\\( v_f \\)).\n2. Calculate the change in velocity (\\( \\Delta v = v_f - v_i \\)).\n3. Measure the time interval during which the change in velocity occurred (\\( \\Delta t \\)).\n4. Divide the change in velocity by the time interval to get the average acceleration:\n\n\\[ a_{\\text{avg}} = \\frac{v_f - v_i}{t_f - t_i} \\]\n\nwhere \\( t_f \\) is the final time and \\( t_i \\) is the initial time.\n\nExample:\nSuppose a car accelerates from 10 m/s to 30 m/s over a period of 5 seconds.\nInitial velocity (\\( v_i \\)) = 10 m/s\nFinal velocity (\\( v_f \\)) = 30 m/s\nChange in velocity (\\( \\Delta v \\)) = 30 m/s - 10 m/s = 20 m/s\nChange in time (\\( \\Delta t \\)) = 5 s\n\nAverage acceleration (\\( a_{\\text{avg}} \\)) = \\( \\frac{20 \\text{ m/s}}{5 \\text{ s}} = 4 \\text{ m/s}^2 \\)\n\nTherefore, the average acceleration is \\( 4 \\text{ m/s}^2 \\).",
